const int kNumThreads = 4;

void evaluateAgents(std::vector<Agent>& agents) {
  int num_agents = agents.size();

  // Split agents into kNumThreads batches
  int batch_size = num_agents / kNumThreads;
  std::vector<std::vector<Agent>::iterator> batch_start(kNumThreads);
  std::vector<std::vector<Agent>::iterator> batch_end(kNumThreads);
  for (int i = 0; i < kNumThreads; ++i) {
    batch_start[i] = agents.begin() + i * batch_size;
    batch_end[i] = i == kNumThreads - 1 ? agents.end() : agents.begin() + (i + 1) * batch_size;
  }

  // Evaluate fitness scores in parallel
  std::vector<std::thread> threads;
  for (int i = 0; i < kNumThreads; ++i) {
    threads.emplace_back([batch_start, batch_end](){
      for (auto it = batch_start[i]; it != batch_end[i]; ++it) {
        it->fitness_score = it->evaluateFitness();
      }
    });
  }
  for (auto& thread : threads) {
    thread.join();
  }
}
```

In this example, the `evaluateAgents` function takes in a vector of `Agent`s and evaluates their fitness scores in parallel using `kNumThreads` threads. First, the function splits the `agents` vector into `kNumThreads` batches of roughly equal size. Then, it launches `kNumThreads` threads, each of which evaluates the fitness scores of the agents in one batch. Finally, the function waits for all threads to finish before returning. 

